{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:11:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:11:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.55,0.29,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57107"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/351"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42566"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"1293"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43792"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57107"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is being investigated for recurrent melaena. Over the last two months he has had three episodes of dark red blood in his stool. He is otherwise asymptomatic. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Two endoscopies and two colonoscopies have both been normal. His haemoglobin is 90 g/L (135-180).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conventional angiography","Red cell scan","Capsule endoscopy","CT angiogram","MR enterography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll the investigations listed have a role in the detection of various different types of obscure gastrointestinal haemorrhage. The use of the term \u0027obscure\u0027 infers that the source of haemorrhage has not been immediately obvious, and even with repeated investigation of the oesophagus, stomach, duodenum and colon (the most common sites of a bleed from within the gut) the cause has not been found. The ideal initial investigation for a patient with obscure gastrointestinal bleeding is upper endoscopy and colonoscopy. If this - when repeated - does not yield the site of bleeding, then one of the listed investigations must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is very useful in the detection of a site of bleed - when the bleed is actually occurring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Econventional angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E might be done when the site of the bleed has been identified and for various reasons it is decided that radiological obliteration of the site is the most appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E red cell scan \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be considered when the bleeding is occurring but at too slow a rate to allow the site to be identified by CT angiography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMR enterography\u003C/strong\u003E might help in the identification of lesions within the small bowel (not accessible by endoscopy or colonoscopy), but would not, by itself, be able to confirm that any identifiable lesion was the cause of the bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECapsule endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would allow common small bowel sources of bleeding, particularly angiodysplastic lesions (not seen on MR enterogram), to be diagnosed. Of all the options, capsule endoscopy appears to have the highest diagnostic yield when looking for causes of obscure, but active haemorrhage. A recent study in the American Journal of Gastroenterology reported a 53.3% detection rate with capsule endoscopy compared with a 20% rate using conventional angiography.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In haemodynamically stable patients, capsule endoscopy is the preferred investigation to identify the source of presumed small bowel bleeding."],"references":["Leung WK, Ho SS, Suen BY, Lai LH, Yu S, Ng EK, et al. Capsule endoscopy or angiography in patients with acute overt obscure gastrointestinal bleeding: a prospective randomized study with long-term follow-up. Am J Gastroenterol. 2012;107(9):1370-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22825363/","Thakral D, Stein DJ, Saltzman JR. Diagnosis of Occult and Obscure Gastrointestinal Bleeding. Gastrointest Endoscopy Clin N Am 2024 34:317\u201329."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42566"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42566"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T17:12:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T17:13:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"351"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57107"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"da